00:41:25,774 --> 00:41:27,067
- Excuse me.
- Would you...?

825
00:41:27,151 --> 00:41:29,653
[indistinct chattering]

826
00:41:29,737 --> 00:41:32,537
We negate that the cost of college
education is outweighed by benefits.

827
00:41:35,784 --> 00:41:38,704
We affirm the costs of a college
education are outweighed by the benefits.

828
00:41:40,372 --> 00:41:42,541
[Lona continues speaking rapidly]

829
00:41:42,625 --> 00:41:43,876
That's the right height.

830
00:41:43,959 --> 00:41:45,437
Look at the difference of the height.

831
00:41:45,461 --> 00:41:47,272
[Bennett] ...indicates college graduates
are more likely to earn higher salaries

832
00:41:47,296 --> 00:41:49,173
pay more taxes, taxed at a higher rate...

833
00:41:49,256 --> 00:41:51,133
[girl speaking rapidly]

834
00:41:53,385 --> 00:41:54,821
- This is our area.
- Get it out of my area.

835
00:41:54,845 --> 00:41:56,430
We're on a team. This is our area.

836
00:41:56,514 --> 00:41:59,394
Without college educations, prospective
employees will be ill-equipped...

837
00:41:59,642 --> 00:42:01,894
[stammers, then speaks rapidly]

838
00:42:03,729 --> 00:42:05,105
That's why you must vote neg.

839
00:42:05,189 --> 00:42:06,649
- [timer beeps]
- [clears throat]

840
00:42:09,610 --> 00:42:11,111
[table squeaks]

841
00:42:14,198 --> 00:42:15,866
Is anyone not ready?

842
00:42:16,450 --> 00:42:17,493
[clears throat]

843
00:42:17,910 --> 00:42:20,579
Our high school is inferior to yours.

844
00:42:21,247 --> 00:42:23,666
[speaks Spanish]

845
00:42:23,749 --> 00:42:25,501
We'd bet you money, if we had any.

846
00:42:25,584 --> 00:42:27,503
[Dana]
We have no fancy research databases,

847
00:42:27,586 --> 00:42:29,338
no personal laptop computers.

848
00:42:29,421 --> 00:42:32,883
No debate coaches with
national championships on their résumé.

849
00:42:32,967 --> 00:42:36,011
No, our debate coach works at Sears
on the weekends

850
00:42:36,095 --> 00:42:37,680
- because he needs the money.
- [sighs]

851
00:42:37,763 --> 00:42:39,974
So the moment that timer starts,

852
00:42:40,057 --> 00:42:42,893
we're already ten steps behind
and are forced to play catch-up.

853
00:42:42,977 --> 00:42:44,895
Well, we don't have to worry about them.

854
00:42:44,979 --> 00:42:46,772
What? Why not?

855
00:42:46,855 --> 00:42:48,524
They're good, really good.

856
00:42:48,607 --> 00:42:52,236
This approach rarely wins. Replacing
feelings for facts is not debate.

857
00:42:52,319 --> 00:42:53,612
The judges will see through it.

858
00:42:53,696 --> 00:42:55,781
- Have you ever debated against it?
- Have you?

859
00:42:55,864 --> 00:42:58,492
Jania Santos. Want to hear her story?

860
00:42:58,576 --> 00:42:59,970
She was top of her high school class.

861
00:42:59,994 --> 00:43:02,079
Went to a fancy liberal arts school
on the East Coast

862
00:43:02,162 --> 00:43:04,623
and graduated
with a BA in European History.

863
00:43:04,707 --> 00:43:06,307
[Jasmine]
And guess what she's doing now?

864
00:43:06,333 --> 00:43:07,251
[Dana speaking in Spanish]

865
00:43:07,334 --> 00:43:08,168
Sears.

866
00:43:08,252 --> 00:43:10,254
She's working at Sears
with our debate coach!

867
00:43:10,337 --> 00:43:12,232
You know, what are these colleges
really offering

868
00:43:12,256 --> 00:43:14,008
if they're not offering careers?

869
00:43:14,091 --> 00:43:15,801
- It's bullshit!
- It's bullshit!

870
00:43:15,884 --> 00:43:19,221
All I'm saying is how do we prepare
to debate someone's personal experiences?

871
00:43:19,305 --> 00:43:20,991
There's no way
to anticipate what they'll say.

872
00:43:21,015 --> 00:43:23,615
No. We dismiss it as contrary
to the framework of the debate topic

873
00:43:23,684 --> 00:43:26,162
and the judges will agree
that what they're saying is meaningless.

874
00:43:26,186 --> 00:43:28,480
You think what they're saying
is meaningless?

875
00:43:28,564 --> 00:43:30,858
I think that the facts will always win
and you do, too.

876
00:43:31,609 --> 00:43:35,613
[speaking rapidly]

877
00:43:38,365 --> 00:43:39,950
[school bell ringing]

878
00:43:40,743 --> 00:43:42,036
[Kathy] See what I told you?

879
00:43:42,119 --> 00:43:44,472
Honestly, they shouldn't even
give a trophy for a qualifier.

880
00:43:44,496 --> 00:43:45,414
You can have it.

881
00:43:45,497 --> 00:43:47,333
You earned it. Give yourself a break.

882
00:43:47,416 --> 00:43:50,294
- [groans] I don't have time for breaks.
- You're nervous, aren't you?

883
00:43:50,377 --> 00:43:52,796
- About State?
- No, about getting into Harvard.

884
00:43:52,880 --> 00:43:53,964
It's this Friday.

885
00:43:54,048 --> 00:43:55,650
- You told them you qualified?
- Yeah, I did.

886
00:43:55,674 --> 00:43:58,427
You're a four-time qualifier.
That's amazing!

887
00:43:58,510 --> 00:44:00,095
Yeah, but am I gonna get in?

888
00:44:00,179 --> 00:44:01,656
- You'll do great.
- You don't know that.

889
00:44:01,680 --> 00:44:02,848
They'd be lucky to have you.

890
00:44:02,931 --> 00:44:04,534
Look, Harvard has a five percent
acceptance rate.

891
00:44:04,558 --> 00:44:07,353
That means that there's a 95 percent
chance that I don't get in.

892
00:44:07,436 --> 00:44:09,188
- Maybe you're different.
- Maybe I'm not.

893
00:44:09,271 --> 00:44:10,391
Maybe I'm not any different.

894
00:44:10,439 --> 00:44:13,567
Maybe I'm just another robot
who spends too much time in the library.

895
00:44:13,651 --> 00:44:16,654
- Is that really what you think?
- I don't know and neither do you.

896
00:44:20,240 --> 00:44:21,240
Okay.

897
00:44:22,076 --> 00:44:23,661
Fine.

898
00:44:23,744 --> 00:44:24,578
You're right.

899
00:44:24,662 --> 00:44:25,496
[sighs]

900
00:44:25,579 --> 00:44:29,249
It doesn't look good.
In fact, it looks pretty shitty.

901
00:44:29,333 --> 00:44:32,711
We're talking about Harvard, so the odds
are clearly stacked against you

902
00:44:32,795 --> 00:44:34,672
and it's more than likely
you'll be rejected.

903
00:44:36,048 --> 00:44:37,508
Is that better?

904
00:44:37,591 --> 00:44:39,885
Lona, I don't have a clue
where you're gonna end up.

905
00:44:39,968 --> 00:44:41,220
Not in a year.

906
00:44:41,804 --> 00:44:43,639
Not ten years from now.

907
00:44:43,722 --> 00:44:45,891
We don't know what's gonna happen.
Nobody does.

908
00:44:48,519 --> 00:44:50,979
No matter where you go,
will you promise me something?

909
00:44:51,063 --> 00:44:52,231
What?

910
00:44:52,815 --> 00:44:53,899
You're not gonna like it.

911
00:44:55,609 --> 00:44:59,988
In fact, many extremely successful people
will completely disagree with me.

912
00:45:00,697 --> 00:45:04,535
I don't know. I hesitate
to even bring it up. Maybe I'll just...

913
00:45:04,618 --> 00:45:05,818
Where are you going with this?

914
00:45:09,081 --> 00:45:10,707
When I started working here,

915
00:45:11,917 --> 00:45:12,917
that wall was empty.

916
00:45:16,088 --> 00:45:18,132
That bookcase was empty.

917
00:45:20,676 --> 00:45:23,679
And then kids like you left.

918
00:45:24,638 --> 00:45:28,183
And they got into their dream school,
or they didn't.

919
00:45:29,435 --> 00:45:32,020
But all of them went on to do stuff.

920
00:45:33,188 --> 00:45:34,231
Make stuff.

921
00:45:35,232 --> 00:45:36,692
And so they sent me stuff.

922
00:45:38,861 --> 00:45:42,364
And I'm not sure
but I think that's a life.

923
00:45:47,619 --> 00:45:49,204
Wherever you end up, kiddo,

924
00:45:50,456 --> 00:45:51,498
have fun.

925
00:46:00,799 --> 00:46:02,676
[sighs]

926
00:46:04,011 --> 00:46:05,137
[Amy groans]

927
00:46:06,305 --> 00:46:07,514
[chuckles]

928
00:46:07,598 --> 00:46:09,475
[crickets chirping]

929
00:46:17,232 --> 00:46:20,694
[breathes heavily]

930
00:46:25,532 --> 00:46:26,532
Now. Now.

931
00:46:28,911 --> 00:46:30,579
Okay, let's type in my password.

932
00:46:30,662 --> 00:46:32,414
[keyboard clacking]

933
00:46:36,627 --> 00:46:38,795
Okay, here we go.

934
00:46:38,879 --> 00:46:41,548
No matter what happens,
I love you and I'm so proud of you.

935
00:46:41,632 --> 00:46:42,674
Your father would be, too.

936
00:46:43,592 --> 00:46:45,260
[chuckles]

937
00:46:45,844 --> 00:46:46,844
[Lona] All right.

938
00:46:48,138 --> 00:46:49,515
[clicks]

939
00:46:49,890 --> 00:46:52,976
[breathes out]

940
00:46:59,525 --> 00:47:01,109
Here it is. Here it is.

