987
00:49:55,701 --> 00:49:56,719
This is your future, Bennett.

988
00:49:56,743 --> 00:49:58,745
I'm gonna need you
to take it a bit more seriously.

989
00:49:58,829 --> 00:50:00,455
You don't think I know that?

990
00:50:01,039 --> 00:50:02,809
You know how much time
I've spent trying to get in?

991
00:50:02,833 --> 00:50:04,543
How many classes I've taken?

992
00:50:04,626 --> 00:50:06,253
How many nights I've gotten no sleep?

993
00:50:06,336 --> 00:50:09,005
I wanted it bad. [stammers] But so what?

994
00:50:09,089 --> 00:50:11,258
Will I not have a future
if I don't go to Yale?

995
00:50:11,341 --> 00:50:13,009
Not as bright a future.

996
00:50:15,220 --> 00:50:16,346
[scoffs]

997
00:50:17,639 --> 00:50:18,682
Wow!

998
00:50:18,765 --> 00:50:19,765
So it's all bullshit?

999
00:50:19,808 --> 00:50:20,934
What?

1000
00:50:21,017 --> 00:50:22,203
You give out college scholarships

1001
00:50:22,227 --> 00:50:23,746
- to poor kids who can't afford it.
- Bennett.

1002
00:50:23,770 --> 00:50:26,416
They're not going to Yale or Harvard.
You send them to public school.

1003
00:50:26,440 --> 00:50:29,818
- Why do you do it if it's such a waste?
- Because they have nothing!

1004
00:50:30,610 --> 00:50:33,447
We give them something to hold on to.

1005
00:50:33,530 --> 00:50:34,364
You...

1006
00:50:34,448 --> 00:50:37,159
Bennett, you come from everything.

1007
00:50:37,242 --> 00:50:39,870
And you expect everything!

1008
00:50:39,953 --> 00:50:41,580
And anything less is a disappointment.

1009
00:50:41,663 --> 00:50:43,832
- No.
- No. That's what you're saying.

1010
00:50:43,915 --> 00:50:45,101
The expectations are so high...

1011
00:50:45,125 --> 00:50:48,128
Yale made it possible for a girl like me
who comes from nothing

1012
00:50:48,211 --> 00:50:50,505
to make something of herself.

1013
00:50:50,589 --> 00:50:52,841
- So it's Yale or nothing?
- That's not what I'm saying.

1014
00:50:52,924 --> 00:50:54,134
Then what are you saying, Mom?

1015
00:50:54,843 --> 00:50:56,052
Hmm?

1016
00:50:57,387 --> 00:50:58,972
Yeah. That's what I thought.

1017
00:50:59,973 --> 00:51:00,973
Bennett.

1018
00:51:04,603 --> 00:51:06,688
- [birds chirping]
- [door closing]

1019
00:51:06,772 --> 00:51:08,356
[sad music playing]

1020
00:51:08,440 --> 00:51:09,941
[telephone ringing]

1021
00:51:12,319 --> 00:51:13,528
[Lona knocking on door]

1022
00:51:15,155 --> 00:51:16,698
[door thudding]

1023
00:51:24,748 --> 00:51:25,582
[sighs]

1024
00:51:25,665 --> 00:51:30,879
♪ I see you runnin' ♪

1025
00:51:34,007 --> 00:51:35,383
[telephone ringing]

1026
00:51:35,634 --> 00:51:37,177
[Bennett and Lona sighing]

1027
00:51:41,598 --> 00:51:43,767
[man] Good morning.
What do you have for me?

1028
00:51:44,601 --> 00:51:46,686
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

1029
00:51:53,485 --> 00:51:55,153
Can I help you guys?

1030
00:51:55,237 --> 00:51:57,197
I was just waiting to see Kathy.

1031
00:51:57,739 --> 00:51:59,115
Yeah, me, too.

1032
00:52:02,536 --> 00:52:03,536
[sighs]

1033
00:52:03,578 --> 00:52:04,579
I'm sorry. Uh...

1034
00:52:05,997 --> 00:52:07,958
Kathy passed away.

1035
00:52:09,793 --> 00:52:12,838
Kathy, the guidance counselor.
The candy...

1036
00:52:14,881 --> 00:52:18,343
Kathy was in an accident...

1037
00:52:18,426 --> 00:52:20,887
after school on Friday.

1038
00:52:23,223 --> 00:52:24,057
I'm...

1039
00:52:24,140 --> 00:52:25,308
[sighs]

1040
00:52:28,019 --> 00:52:30,397
...about to make the announcement
to the rest of the school.

1041
00:52:32,816 --> 00:52:33,816
I'm so sorry.

1042
00:52:43,827 --> 00:52:46,371
[Lona sobbing]

1043
00:52:58,133 --> 00:52:59,551
[birds chirping]

1044
00:52:59,634 --> 00:53:02,387
["Misery and Mountains, Arrows and Bows"
playing]

1045
00:53:06,892 --> 00:53:11,021
♪ My body's broken ♪

1046
00:53:12,564 --> 00:53:16,651
♪ I'm not ashamed ♪

1047
00:53:18,194 --> 00:53:22,407
♪ Dangerous token ♪

1048
00:53:23,783 --> 00:53:27,537
♪ Guilty with pain ♪

1049
00:53:29,247 --> 00:53:33,001
♪ Tell them my story ♪

1050
00:53:33,877 --> 00:53:37,422
♪ Beginning to end ♪

1051
00:53:38,548 --> 00:53:42,761
♪ Bring me my sweetheart ♪

1052
00:53:42,844 --> 00:53:46,556
♪ I wanna see him ♪

1053
00:54:13,458 --> 00:54:16,670
On the way over, I sort of thought
we were gonna see Kathy here.

1054
00:54:17,921 --> 00:54:19,381
I know that doesn't make any sense.

1055
00:54:19,464 --> 00:54:23,677
But, I mean,
it's, like, her funeral, and so...

1056
00:54:24,552 --> 00:54:26,429
she should be here, you know?

1057
00:54:28,098 --> 00:54:29,098
Yeah.

1058
00:54:29,975 --> 00:54:31,893
I felt that way about your dad's service.

1059
00:54:33,979 --> 00:54:35,772
You remember my dad's service?

1060
00:54:37,857 --> 00:54:38,858
We were six.

1061
00:54:40,735 --> 00:54:42,904
It was the first funeral
I had ever been to.

1062
00:54:44,739 --> 00:54:46,866
Yeah, mine, too.

1063
00:54:47,951 --> 00:54:48,951
[sniffs]

1064
00:54:52,622 --> 00:54:53,707
[clicks tongue]

1065
00:54:56,584 --> 00:54:57,584
Hey, uh...

1066
00:54:58,420 --> 00:55:00,171
I watched that fast food documentary.

1067
00:55:00,255 --> 00:55:01,255
[scoffs]

1068
00:55:01,881 --> 00:55:03,008
You were right.

1069
00:55:03,091 --> 00:55:06,344
Eating that junk food
could seriously damage your organs.

1070
00:55:06,428 --> 00:55:07,971
I told you.

1071
00:55:08,054 --> 00:55:09,806
Yeah. Milkshakes are no good.

1072
00:55:09,889 --> 00:55:11,057
[chuckles]

1073
00:55:11,141 --> 00:55:12,183
And fries.

1074
00:55:15,311 --> 00:55:16,980
[ducks quacking]

1075
00:55:26,239 --> 00:55:27,239
Did you get in?

1076
00:55:29,159 --> 00:55:30,159
No.

1077
00:55:31,411 --> 00:55:32,411
You?

1078
00:55:34,664 --> 00:55:35,664
No.

1079
00:55:42,756 --> 00:55:44,049
What did we do it for?

1080
00:55:46,176 --> 00:55:47,635
What?

1081
00:55:47,719 --> 00:55:48,719
Everything.

1082
00:55:50,138 --> 00:55:52,557
I mean, I don't think
we were ever really high schoolers.

1083
00:55:53,391 --> 00:55:56,478
Are you telling me that I dreamed up
all those classes and tests?

1084
00:55:56,561 --> 00:55:57,896
No, I'm saying we never...

1085
00:56:00,065 --> 00:56:01,775
How many football games did you go to?

1086
00:56:03,860 --> 00:56:05,278
I don't believe in football.

1087
00:56:05,361 --> 00:56:08,031
Neither do I. How about parties?

1088
00:56:08,615 --> 00:56:10,450
I believe in them even less.

1089
00:56:10,533 --> 00:56:12,494
What about goofing off in class?

1090
00:56:12,577 --> 00:56:14,537
Or passing stupid notes?

1091
00:56:15,288 --> 00:56:17,415
Or laughing at a joke so hard
that you start crying?

1092
00:56:17,999 --> 00:56:19,459
Is that high school to you?

1093
00:56:19,542 --> 00:56:20,542
I don't know.

1094
00:56:21,503 --> 00:56:23,421
I was too busy with...

1095
00:56:23,505 --> 00:56:28,384
with homework, tests and debate.

1096
00:56:28,468 --> 00:56:29,886
Yeah, that's high school.

1097
00:56:31,679 --> 00:56:34,641
Okay, if it is,
how come you don't have tons of friends?

1098
00:56:40,105 --> 00:56:41,439
Shut up. You don't know me.

1099
00:56:52,992 --> 00:56:53,992
Hey.

1100
00:56:55,829 --> 00:56:56,746
If you're anything like me,

1101
00:56:56,830 --> 00:56:59,040
Kathy was the only person
you could really talk to.

1102
00:57:02,418 --> 00:57:05,713
What if everything we went through
will be the exact same in college?

1103
00:57:08,466 --> 00:57:09,467
You think so?

1104
00:57:11,678 --> 00:57:14,180
I'm pretty sure the Ivy League
has football games and parties,

1105
00:57:14,264 --> 00:57:18,685
and there's always gonna be someone
passing stupid drawings.

1106
00:57:24,399 --> 00:57:26,109
What's your point?

1107
00:57:27,694 --> 00:57:29,028
I wish I had one.

1108
00:57:34,701 --> 00:57:36,453
We could really use Kathy right now.

1109
00:57:39,789 --> 00:57:40,999
Yeah.

1110
00:57:50,550 --> 00:57:52,719
[man on TV]
...and what makes this table so expensive

1111
00:57:52,802 --> 00:57:54,596
is it's made of desert ironwood

1112
00:57:54,679 --> 00:57:58,766
from a perennial flowering tree
of the Fabaceae family.

1113
00:57:58,850 --> 00:58:01,394
[woman on TV]
Desert ironwood? Are you sure?

1114
00:58:01,978 --> 00:58:04,522
You don't come across
desert ironwood every day, so yes.

1115
00:58:04,606 --> 00:58:08,234
Don't get me wrong, it's really nice
having you here on the couch,

1116
00:58:09,611 --> 00:58:10,987
but it's just not you.

1117
00:58:12,697 --> 00:58:13,698
[inhales, breathes out]

1118
00:58:14,616 --> 00:58:16,701
State tournament's in a few weeks.

1119
00:58:18,286 --> 00:58:19,305
I'm sorry it's with Bennett...

1120
00:58:19,329 --> 00:58:21,289
Is there anything that you like
about Julia?

1121
00:58:23,458 --> 00:58:24,458
What?

1122
00:58:25,793 --> 00:58:27,128
Anything at all.

1123
00:58:35,762 --> 00:58:37,180
[sighs]

1124
00:58:38,515 --> 00:58:43,978
Her first ever campaign slogan
was "Julia Russell is the right stuff."

1125
00:58:44,062 --> 00:58:45,647
[scoffs] Never mind.

1126
00:58:45,730 --> 00:58:49,359
Come on!
New Kids on the Block? That's amazing.

1127
00:58:50,777 --> 00:58:55,073
We ran against each other
for class president and I kicked her ass.

1128
00:58:55,156 --> 00:58:57,951
That's right. The cheerleader
took down the bookworm.

1129
00:58:58,785 --> 00:59:01,829
It was brutal, though. We were vicious.

1130
00:59:01,913 --> 00:59:03,373
[chuckles]

1131
00:59:03,456 --> 00:59:04,958
Still bugs her.

1132
00:59:08,378 --> 00:59:09,462
I'll tell you a secret.

1133
00:59:12,423 --> 00:59:13,591
I vote for her.

1134
00:59:15,134 --> 00:59:16,386
She gets things done.

1135
00:59:16,469 --> 00:59:17,762
[scoffs]

1136
00:59:17,845 --> 00:59:21,224
She was on every Top 30 Under 30 list.

1137
00:59:22,475 --> 00:59:24,227
And then she adopted Bennett.

1138
00:59:24,310 --> 00:59:26,062
And then she became a senator.

1139
00:59:27,480 --> 00:59:30,733
And she seems to balance it all
on her own.

1140
00:59:33,486 --> 00:59:35,321
She's a great mom. It's very annoying.

1141
00:59:38,658 --> 00:59:39,951
I'm gonna finish my show.

1142
00:59:41,536 --> 00:59:42,537
Leave me alone.

1143
00:59:43,246 --> 00:59:45,373
[man speaking on TV]

1144
00:59:49,252 --> 00:59:53,881
[Mr. Johnson] So, after four years
of not agreeing on anything,

1145
00:59:53,965 --> 00:59:57,427
the first thing you both agree on
is to not compete in the state tournament.

1146
00:59:59,345 --> 01:00:00,847
So you both agree for the first time

1147
01:00:00,930 --> 01:00:03,141
and now you're both silent
for the first time.

1148
01:00:09,606 --> 01:00:11,316
Since when are you two the quitting kind?

1149
01:00:12,942 --> 01:00:16,529
So, you didn't get
into your dream schools.

1150
01:00:16,613 --> 01:00:20,033
There are greater tragedies in this world.

1151
01:00:21,075 --> 01:00:23,703
What, were you trying to prove
to your moms that you... what?

1152
01:00:24,954 --> 01:00:26,331
Prove what?

1153
01:00:27,081 --> 01:00:30,251
Oh, you two are so full of crap.

1154
01:00:30,335 --> 01:00:32,712
You're five-foot nothing.
You're a hundred and nothing.

1155
01:00:32,795 --> 01:00:35,048
You hardly got
a speck of athletic ability.

1156
01:00:35,131 --> 01:00:37,234
And you hung in with the best
college football team in the land

1157
01:00:37,258 --> 01:00:38,258
for the past two years.

1158
01:00:38,301 --> 01:00:40,011
And you're both about
to walk out of here

1159
01:00:40,094 --> 01:00:43,389
with a degree
from the University of Notre Dame.

1160
01:00:45,141 --> 01:00:46,702
Mr. Johnson, what are you talking about?

1161
01:00:46,726 --> 01:00:49,562
Oh, come on.
Don't tell me you've never seen Rudy.

1162
01:00:49,646 --> 01:00:53,691
That is one of the best, most recognizable
motivational speeches in all of film.

1163
01:00:53,775 --> 01:00:55,777
Everybody loves Rudy.

1164
01:00:56,486 --> 01:00:57,862
- What's your point?
- [sighs]

1165
01:00:57,945 --> 01:01:00,615
If you add state champions
to your résumé next month,

1166
01:01:00,698 --> 01:01:02,659
that's only gonna help
your chances everywhere.

1167
01:01:03,618 --> 01:01:05,995
I guarantee there won't be
a week in your life that goes by

1168
01:01:06,079 --> 01:01:10,458
that you won't regret walking out
and letting them get the best of you.

1169
01:01:11,417 --> 01:01:13,461
Do you hear me clear enough?

1170
01:01:14,212 --> 01:01:17,548
"I rode the bench for two years.

1171
01:01:17,632 --> 01:01:20,218
I thought I wasn't being played
because of my color."

1172
01:01:20,301 --> 01:01:21,469
Is this that movie again?

1173
01:01:21,552 --> 01:01:24,430
I am honestly nailing it here
but I'd like to go from the beginning,

1174
01:01:24,514 --> 01:01:25,807
- uninterrupt...
- Just stop.

1175
01:01:29,018 --> 01:01:30,436
I do things by myself.

1176
01:01:30,520 --> 01:01:33,564
I've always done things
by myself my whole life.

1177
01:01:35,149 --> 01:01:38,444
I want to win so bad
that it physically hurts.

1178
01:01:40,113 --> 01:01:42,573
Maybe it'll help me get into school,
maybe it won't.

1179
01:01:43,783 --> 01:01:44,783
[sighs]

1180
01:01:45,368 --> 01:01:47,203
I just... I want to win.

1181
01:01:48,496 --> 01:01:50,206
What are you saying?

1182
01:01:50,289 --> 01:01:53,459
I'm saying that we should play football.

1183
01:01:55,962 --> 01:01:56,962
Then let's play.

1184
01:01:58,214 --> 01:02:00,633
Okay. Rudy from the top.

1185
01:02:01,300 --> 01:02:02,468
[door opening]

1186
01:02:02,552 --> 01:02:05,072
[Lona] Mom, Bennett and I are gonna be
working in here for a while.

1187
01:02:05,096 --> 01:02:06,472
- Okay.
- Hi, Mrs. Skinner.

1188
01:02:06,973 --> 01:02:08,391
Wait, what?

1189
01:02:09,016 --> 01:02:10,393
Whoa!

1190
01:02:10,476 --> 01:02:11,644
[chuckles]

1191
01:02:13,104 --> 01:02:15,940
- Thank you for having me, Ms. Skinner.
- Of course, Bennett.

1192
01:02:23,364 --> 01:02:24,991
Mom, you should put on some pants.

1193
01:02:26,909 --> 01:02:29,245
[Bennett] You could focus on aff.
I could focus on neg.

1194
01:02:30,663 --> 01:02:32,957
[Bennett speaking indistinctly]

1195
01:02:33,040 --> 01:02:35,126
Can I get you something to eat, Bennett?

1196
01:02:35,209 --> 01:02:37,086
Uh, no, I'm okay.

1197
01:02:38,755 --> 01:02:39,672
We're okay.

1198
01:02:39,756 --> 01:02:40,757
Something to drink?

1199
01:02:40,840 --> 01:02:44,260
- We've got water, juice, soda, beer.
- Beer?

1200
01:02:45,178 --> 01:02:47,930
[stammers] I'm fine. Thank you.

1201
01:02:48,014 --> 01:02:49,214
Well, I made cookies yesterday

1202
01:02:49,265 --> 01:02:51,851
so I'll go get some of those
and, um, some milk.

1203
01:02:56,481 --> 01:02:58,483
I'm sorry.
Can you please give me a second?

1204
01:03:01,611 --> 01:03:04,947
- What's the matter with you?
- You didn't tell me he was coming over.

1205
01:03:05,031 --> 01:03:07,784
- I'm allowed to bring someone over.
- But him?

1206
01:03:07,867 --> 01:03:08,701
[groans]

1207
01:03:08,785 --> 01:03:12,872
The last thing we need is Julia knowing
what this place looks like.

1208
01:03:12,955 --> 01:03:14,540
Or my exercise regimen.

1209
01:03:15,666 --> 01:03:16,876
Or my lack of pants.

1210
01:03:16,959 --> 01:03:20,129
- He doesn't care about that stuff.
- Yeah, well, she does.

1211
01:03:20,213 --> 01:03:24,383
Tell him the dining room table
is desert ironwood

1212
01:03:24,467 --> 01:03:27,595
[Amy] from the penal flowering tree
of the Fibonacci family.

1213
01:03:27,678 --> 01:03:28,846
[chuckles]

1214
01:03:28,930 --> 01:03:31,390
- You're being ridiculous.
- No, I'm not.

1215
01:03:31,474 --> 01:03:32,308
Get back out there.

1216
01:03:32,391 --> 01:03:34,578
You don't want him to think
we're talking about him behind his back.

1217
01:03:34,602 --> 01:03:35,812
I'm not. You are.

1218
01:03:38,815 --> 01:03:39,982
[sighs]

1219
01:03:41,108 --> 01:03:42,108
Thank you.

1220
01:03:42,151 --> 01:03:43,277
[chuckles]

1221
01:03:45,363 --> 01:03:46,364
Wow.

1222
01:03:47,824 --> 01:03:48,824
Hmm.

1223
01:03:51,536 --> 01:03:52,411
Mm.

1224
01:03:52,495 --> 01:03:54,080
Wow.

1225
01:03:54,163 --> 01:03:56,916
They're my mom's recipe.
I'm sure you've had better.

1226
01:03:56,999 --> 01:03:58,918
No, I don't think so.

1227
01:04:00,711 --> 01:04:04,674
I like to let the cookie soak in there,
you know. It enriches the flavor.

1228
01:04:04,757 --> 01:04:05,967
[chuckles]

1229
01:04:06,676 --> 01:04:07,676
You're weird.

1230
01:04:08,302 --> 01:04:10,054
["Backroads" playing]

1231
01:04:16,602 --> 01:04:18,479
For our guest.

1232
01:04:20,189 --> 01:04:21,774
Oh, thank you.

1233
01:04:21,858 --> 01:04:23,901
- [Julia chuckles]
- Whoa!

1234
01:04:24,485 --> 01:04:25,862
Thanks.

1235
01:04:25,945 --> 01:04:26,945
Try it.

1236
01:04:29,407 --> 01:04:33,119
[Bennett] Not... No, no, no.
Not a dip. Dunk it.

1237
01:04:33,202 --> 01:04:35,389
- [Bennett] Dunk it and hold it. Hold...
- [Lona] I did dunk it.

1238
01:04:35,413 --> 01:04:36,413
Oh, my God.

1239
01:04:38,040 --> 01:04:41,002
♪ That I don't like crying ♪

1240
01:04:41,085 --> 01:04:43,963
- No. No.
- Yep.

